  "prompt": "Why do secants have a vertical asymptote?",
  "response": "Let me clarify something important: not all secant functions have a vertical asymptote. The secant function (sec(x)) has vertical asymptotes when the cosine function (cos(x)) equals zero.\n\nSpecifically, vertical asymptotes for sec(x) occur at:\nx = \u03c0/2 + k*\u03c0, where k is any integer\n\nAt these points, cos(x) = 0, which makes sec(x) = 1/cos(x) undefined. This creates vertical asymptotes.\n\nThese points are at 90\u00b0, 270\u00b0, 450\u00b0, etc. on the unit circle, where cosine crosses zero.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on why this happens mathematically?",
